[1
Date: 8 Jan 2001 17:02:42 GMT-3
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Xinhua 30 Dec 2000 [edited

Dengue Fever Virus Type 4 Detected in Costa Rica
-------------------------------------------------
A total of 4 cases of dengue fever have been discovered in the Costa Rican
coastal city of Limon, health authorities confirmed here on Sat 30 Dec 2000.
Xiania Carvajal, Vice Minister of Health, noted that these are cases of
infection with dengue fever virus type 4, a [serotype not previously found
in Costa Rica. "In Costa Rica, there have been cases of infection with
dengue fever virus types 2 and 3, and some years ago, type 1, but never
type 4," she said. "We classify the infections as [less severe, that is,
less serious than with the other serotypes, but we will stay alert just the
same."
According to Carvajal, the 3 other types of dengue fever virus entered
Costa Rica via immigrants from other countries of Central America, where
all 4 types of dengue fever virus [exist. The disease reappeared in Costa
Rica in late 1993, and since then it has affected over 45 000 people.
Dengue viruses, carried by _Aedes_ mosquitoes, cause high fever and
headache, eye and muscle pain. There are 3 different patterns: classic
dengue, hemorrhagic dengue and shock syndrome, the gravest form of dengue
fever. Experts have found that once a person [experiences an infection with
any one type of dengue fever virus, he or she becomes immune to that
virus, but if he or she becomes [infected later by any other type, the
disease can become hemorrhagic.
